post_text:
If you are a sophomore student interested in attending two years of college for free during your last two years of high school, you should apply to Craft Academy at Morehead State or Gatton Academy at WKU.

These are very selective programs for academically motivated students, paid for by the state and private donors. An ACT score is required.

If admitted, you will live on campus in the Academy’s dorm while taking on-campus college classes during your Junior and Senior years.

More information about the schools and programs can be found at: https://www.wku.edu/academy/ and https://www.moreheadstate.edu/Academics/Craft-Academy

Application requirements can be found at: https://www.wku.edu/academy/admissions/requirements.php and https://www.moreheadstate.edu/Academics/Craft-Academy/Prospective-Students/Apply-to-the-Craft-Academy

High School G&T Teacher, Mrs. Booth, is happy to help any student putting together an application. To work with her, please make a request soon using this form: http://bit.ly/GTCounselingRequestForm

post_text:
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: AUGUST 11, 2020

Based on the recommendation made yesterday by Governor Andy Beshear, Scott County Schools will open for in person classes on Monday, October 12, 2020.

Our teachers have been preparing for in person instruction. We want to allow ample time for each teacher to fully prepare for distance learning for all students to start the year. Therefore, school in Scott County is scheduled to begin virtually on September 8.

During the press conference, Governor Beshear recommended that schools delay reopening based on the total number of cases of COVID-19 statewide and the increasing positivity rate as well as the increase in the number of children testing positive for the virus. Scott County Schools will continue to work closely with our local department of public health regarding the safe return to school when recommended by government officials.

Schools will be in contact with families in Scott County soon regarding plans for virtual open house programs. Each school will provide additional information about virtual/distance learning.

post_text:
Scott County elementary schools will conduct virtual open house events on Friday, August 21. On this day, we will post video tours to introduce staff and orient students to their school.

Classroom teachers will contact students to welcome them to their classrooms for the coming year on Thursday, August 20. Students and families are encouraged to watch videos from all teachers within their grade level because there is a possibility that classroom assignments could change as students transition between in person and virtual instruction.

Kindergarten students will tour their school in person when schools conduct Brigance assessments. Each school will contact registered kindergarten students directly to arrange these assessments before the start of school.

Families may contact the school of attendance with questions.

We are working on bus routes for the 2020-2021 school year. In light of the current situation, it is important for us to gather information from parents who plan for their children to ride a school bus this year. Please complete one form for each student who will ride a bus. If you have more than one child, you will be given the option to complete another form after choosing SUBMIT at the bottom of the page.

A form is not needed for those students who will be car-riders or those who selected virtual learning.

DEADLINE IS WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 5, 2020 AT 6:00PM.

COVID-19 safety precautions on school buses this year include: masks worn by students and staff, assigned seats, family members sitting together, and loading buses from back to front. Buses will be disinfected between each route.

Submit Transportation Form Here: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScCkLq6DJXCAS8uV8A2ExF6phXHlOFwI60uhIGtj0BbM7R8rA/viewform?usp=sf_link

post_text:
An out of state sports media marketing business is contacting local businesses soliciting money/sponsorship on behalf of SCHS Athletics and GCHS Athletics.

The same company took over $10,000 from local businesses in a similar scam last year. There is currently an open case with the Georgetown Police Department.

Scott County Schools does not allow outside agencies to solicit on behalf of the school system. If your business has been contacted please let us know immediately.

Fundraising on behalf of the Scott County school system and/or using the SCHS/GCHS logos without written permission is not permissible.

We are very thankful to ALL of our longtime and loyal local and corporate sponsors. Your support helps our athletic programs thrive and we do not want our dedicated partners to be taken advantage of by dishonest solicitation of this type.

post_text:
At the Scott County Board of Education meeting this evening, members of the board took action beginning the process to construct a new building for Scott County High School. The new facility will be located on property already owned by Scott County Schools near the intersection of Long Lick Road and the bypass. It will open in August 2023.

Thanks to the support of the community and the vision and fiscal responsibility of the Scott County Board of Education and district leaders, the new high school facility can be completely constructed without levying an additional nickel tax.

The incoming freshman class, the Class of 2024, will be the first to graduate from the facility. The current Scott County High School building on Cardinal Drive will be renovated to accommodate Scott County Middle School as part of this plan.

Royal Spring Middle School bids a fond farewell to their beloved eighth grade class.

Amazing 8th grade Titans,
Congratulations 8th graders on one of life’s many accomplishments. You have shown perseverance, compassion and pride over the past three years as Royal Spring Titans. The teachers and staff of RSMS are proud of you and we know you will do many great things in the coming years. Stay positive, show empathy to others and be the best version of yourself. Depending on the number submitted, we will try to share as many heartfelt messages as possible throughout the week.

post_text:
May 15, 2020 will be the last day of school for students. Students will have NTI assignments through Friday, May 8. The week of May 11 will be counted as NTI days but will be used to catch students up and ask questions to teachers with no additional assignments for May 11-15.

This change is based on information from the Kentucky Department of Education. If the NTI packet contains assignments for days beyond May 8, they were prepared before this information became available and parents may disregard.

If you indicated access to the internet and a preference to get NTI work for your child online, assignments for May 4-8 will be available on the district website on Tuesday, April 28.

If you or your child indicated that you prefer a paper packet, there are several opportunities to pick up the next batch of assignments. You can stop by your child’s school from 10am-2pm on Tuesday, April 28. Pick up is also available on Wednesday, April 29 from 8-10am or 5-7pm.

As a result of this unprecedented situation, we communicated last week that all events and activities for Scott County Schools are postponed indefinitely.

There have been many questions specifically regarding prom for Great Crossing High School, Phoenix Horizon Community, and Scott County High School. Prom is postponed for all schools.

Based on the best information available, this is an unfortunate but necessary step to limit the exposure to COVID-19 and protect our students, staff, and community.

To see all information released from Scott County Schools regarding COVID-19 visit: https://www.scott.kyschools.us/News/covid19updates.

Spanish versions available.

post_text:
Great Crossing High School and Scott County High School commencement exercises will each be held on the football field at the new Birds Nest Stadium located at 1035 Stamping Ground Road.

Graduation will be on Saturday, May 30, 2020 at 10am for Scott County High School and 2pm for Great Crossing High School.

Working with school leadership, the Scott County Board of Education made the decision to hold the ceremonies on the field to allow more family members and friends to attend.

Please be advised, in the event of inclement weather, the ceremonies may need to be moved indoors and would then be held in the gyms of each respective school. The inclement weather plan would require ticket limits for each school and would include an option for live stream video.

Project Graduation for the Class of 2020 will be held jointly on the evening of May 30 to allow students to share this special time. More details to follow regarding Project Graduation.

Graduation for Phoenix Horizon Community will be May 27, 2020 at 6pm at Scott County High School.

As a district, we are continually thankful for our community and the kindness of local businesses always willing to support Scott County Schools and the many activities, clubs, and teams of our students.

If your business receives a call asking for support or donations, please do not hesitate to call Scott County Schools to confirm authenticity.

There are a number of scams that imply partnership with a school or school group that are for-profit or fraudulent and not connected to our schools or district.

Scott County Schools is partnering with Georgetown Community Hospital to offer a one-time immunization clinic to help families bring students up to date on immunizations required by law.

Families of students in need of immunization updates recently received a letter to notify them. For students to participate in the clinic, parents must complete and return the form attached to the letter. Follow-up information will be sent to families regarding the specific immunizations and permission forms

Clinics will be held at each school in April. Parents are encouraged to participate in the clinic or schedule an appointment with a family physician and provide an updated immunization certificate to the school. Please contact your school nurse for more information.
